I come here for one reason only. The BFC. Oh and the Crawfish Beignets are good too. Seriously though, this is where you should start. Get the burger and whatever else later cause you really need to try Brenda's Fried Chicken first. I've also had their Chicken Etouffee and it was pretty good but in the end it was just a distraction from their delicious fried bird. The service is very good and very quick. I've never actually sat in to eat but I've had Brenda's at the office and have had takeout and the experience even going in to order takeout was phenomenal. If only everywhere else had such smooth processes. I may try the rest of the menu someday but it would be like going to a steakhouse and not getting a steak!

It's called soul food for a reason. If you go on a weekend there will be a long wait, but trust me: it's worth it. I would strongly recommend the shrimp and grits. Could eat that all day every day.

(See pics) Very happy to know that both areas (new and original) of the restaurant sides are open for a couple months and am glad that there were plenty of seats at 8:30am on a Saturday. There's more space among the tables that gives everyone more room. The setting is still better suited for small parties. Apart from what I always order, the original plain beignets, I had the special-- the very hot crispy pork belly dish was cooked to perfection. It was very rich and was excellent with the spicy onion. Always love the cheesy creamy grits and the poached egg made it a big bonus. Service is always fairly good.

Pros: delicious comfort food. Really hits the spot when you're looking for something warm and comforting. We got the catfish beignets, fried chicken eggs benedict, and the shrimp and grits. Recommend all three. Cons: as delicious as the food was, I thought the eggs Benedict was unnecessarily over-sauced. The shrimp and grits had maybe one too many ingredients. The guava mimosa wasn't worth the money. Oh and btw, be prepared to wait for at least 2 hours. Overall: good eats, everyone should visit this place at least once.

After a long, arduous drive to San Francisco, we decided to dine here based on the Yelp reviews. As we walked into the dining establishment, we immediately put our names on the chalkboard. Needless to say, it took us an awful long time until we were seated. I believe we waited for almost 20 minutes as the restaurant was full. While waiting by the door, I noticed that the small interior of the restaurant was decorated by the plethora of mirrors. After what seemed ages, we were finally led to our seats. Now being new here, we certainly did not know what to order. From the hype surrounding this place, we didn't want to order poorly, so we asked the waiter for his recommendations. While talking to us, the waiter seemed occupied with the other patrons and thus, did not make eye contact while talking to us. The waiter soon left abruptly without giving us a coherent recommendation. I decided to dine on the "Kick-Ass Burger" for $9.75. From the menu, the burger consisted of 1/2 pound spiced up ground chuck with caramelized onion, bread & butter pickles, & with their own special sauce on toasted kaiser roll. This burger came with either a side of fries or coleslaw, along with their watermelon pickles. I ordered mine's medium-raw. For 9.75, I expected a performance in my mouth. However, much to my dismay, the first bite of my burger was incredibly salty. At first, I thought it was just me but then I took another bite, after first cleansing my palate with their sweet watermelon house tea. The second bite didn't fare any better. I gave my friends a sample for an unbiased opinion and they told me the same thing--it was salty. Not one to waste food, I tried my best to devour the entire burger, withstanding the barrage of brine-filled bites in order to finish it. Just to be fair, one of my friend ordered the same kick-ass burger and his was as salty as well. This rules out this being an isolated experience. The only thing redeeming in this establishment was probably the chocolate-filled beignet flights (chocolate filled pastry). It wasn't "out-of-this-world" good, but it did amend for the poor performance of the burger somewhat. Their watermelon house tea was 'okay' as well. With the amount of high reviews for Brenda's, I didn't expect anything majestic. I did, however, expect the food to be adequate. However, after dining here, I leave this place with a 1 star review, citing their poor customer service and their non-kick ass burger that was lacking in performance and tasted of the red sea...

The gumbo. Get it and thank me later. The shrimp and grits is also good, but the gumbo would win in a fist fight.

If they can get their tasks sorted out and not seem in such a rush to go home, they could be a five star joint. Disappointed beyond belief at the service (the story is longer but this post is long enough), but food was wonderful. Needs work.

Late post. My bff and I thought, "Hey it's Labor Day. Brenda's shouldn't be too busy. Let's get some breakfast!" We were so wrong... We arrived in the early AM and the line was long. We put our name down on the chalkboard and walked to Philz to get some coffee. We walked back to Brenda's and stood outside and watched each name be crossed off the list. About an hour later, we were finally seated and I was ready to grub! What we ordered: beignet flight (plain, chocolate, granny smith apple and crawfish), hangtown fry (oyster, bacon & scallion scramble) and I believe the shrimp & grits. We made the mistake of eating the beignets first bc they were so sweet and filling. I got so full off of the beignets that I could barely put a dent in my hangtown fry. And OMG that crawfish beignet is AMAZINGGGGG. I wished we had more than just the one to share. I will definitely be coming back! I want to try the watermelon tea next time and order 10 crawfish beignets!

This place should be on your short list. The food, service and people were good. I would definitely come back. Bring a cup of coffee and a book to read, waiting list is long but worth it.

    So I have been visiting the new next door space for a little while.

    New small additional space inside for waiting was a nice touch with coffee serving in the morning while waiting. Chalkboard for putting your name is cute. This place now also caters slightly larger parties and more welcomes families with kids with the new seating design. It's fairly modern comparing with the good old spot. But now they have a much bigger kitchen with better ventilation, even though I missed the old hugging spot.

    There's no longer a break between brunch and dinner which is a rarity. You still have to wait but the line is much more reasonable if you come in the late afternoon.

    I have also had dinner here, a fairly different crowd, more new patrons then the usual frequent crew. The food was also very good. I had the special Jambalaya and it was so much delicious food that I had to take some home.

    I love the fact that you can order a single crawfish beignet dinner time. Not taking over your appetite but still gives you your yearning of the signature dish here.

    Kudos to the really hard working crew from just breakfast and lunch to now dinner until 10pm.

    (See pics)

    10 stars for the beignets!! Okay, let me rewind from the beginning...

    As I always say, breaky is the most important meal / crucial element of the day, whether you have it at 7am on your way to work, or 2/3pm on a lazy weekend.

    I knew about the wait so had a good glass of milk and wore my sensible shoes knowing my lower back would wonder if it's all worth the standing...

    About 45-50 minutes wait (bring your iPhone or a book or a friend) I was seated at the counter. A very cute place with patrons packed next to each other. The atmosphere was intimate yet causal. The servers were extremely friendly with a friendly smile. Me like already! When they say "thanks for waiting" they meant it from the hearts. They know customer service is 1 major component of a restaurant / cafe.

    I might look skinny, but I do eat off the chart. I ordered the beignet flight. which has 1 of each kind. If this is your first time here you should try this (can always take some home if you are too full.) My favourite are definitely the original and crawfish. Chocolate one is very chocolaty that I have trouble consuming all the fillings. The apple one was sweet and warm and welcoming.

    Onto the breaky, I had the Grillades and Grits. The beef was very well marinated for hours that the strong flavour was infused into each cell. The grits was light and a great compliment to the dish. Also love the biscuit that was very crumbly, flaky.

    The coffee with chicory gave a soft bitter kick, which has a good twist like the Vietnamese iced coffee that also uses the same plant.

    The bathroom was in the back when you do get to see the tiny kitchen so be careful and not knock off their pans!

    I'd go back to check if they do beignet takeout since this would be a great treat to a group of friends/colleagues without them waiting in line, especially since this is a place for fewer than a party of 3... it's a cafe, after all...

    After a long, arduous drive to San Francisco, we decided to dine here based on the Yelp reviews. As we walked into the dining establishment, we immediately put our names on the chalkboard. Needless to say, it took us an awful long time until we were seated. I believe we waited for almost 20 minutes as the restaurant was full.

    While waiting by the door, I noticed that the small interior of the restaurant was decorated by the plethora of mirrors. After what seemed ages, we were finally led to our seats.

    Now being new here, we certainly did not know what to order. From the hype surrounding this place, we didn't want to order poorly, so we asked the waiter for his recommendations. While talking to us, the waiter seemed occupied with the other patrons and thus, did not make eye contact while talking to us. The waiter soon left abruptly without giving us a coherent recommendation.

    I decided to dine on the "Kick-Ass Burger" for $9.75. From the menu, the burger consisted of 1/2 pound spiced up ground chuck with caramelized onion,
    bread & butter pickles, & with their own special sauce on toasted kaiser roll. This burger came with either a side of fries or coleslaw, along with their watermelon pickles. I ordered mine's medium-raw.

    For 9.75, I expected a performance in my mouth. However, much to my dismay, the first bite of my burger was incredibly salty. At first, I thought it was just me but then I took another bite, after first cleansing my palate with their sweet watermelon house tea. The second bite didn't fare any better. I gave my friends a sample for an unbiased opinion and they told me the same thing--it was salty. Not one to waste food, I tried my best to devour the entire burger, withstanding the barrage of brine-filled bites in order to finish it.

    Just to be fair, one of my friend ordered the same kick-ass burger and his was as salty as well. This rules out this being an isolated experience.

    The only thing redeeming in this establishment was probably the chocolate-filled beignet flights (chocolate filled pastry). It wasn't "out-of-this-world" good, but it did amend for the poor performance of the burger somewhat. Their watermelon house tea was 'okay' as well.

    With the amount of high reviews for Brenda's, I didn't expect anything majestic. I did, however, expect the food to be adequate. However, after dining here, I leave this place with a 1 star review, citing their poor customer service and their non-kick ass burger that was lacking in performance and tasted of the red sea...

    Late post. My bff and I thought, "Hey it's Labor Day. Brenda's shouldn't be too busy. Let's get some breakfast!" We were so wrong...

    We arrived in the early AM and the line was long. We put our name down on the chalkboard and walked to Philz to get some coffee. We walked back to Brenda's and stood outside and watched each name be crossed off the list. About an hour later, we were finally seated and I was ready to grub!

    What we ordered: beignet flight (plain, chocolate, granny smith apple and crawfish), hangtown fry (oyster, bacon & scallion scramble) and I believe the shrimp & grits. We made the mistake of eating the beignets first bc they were so sweet and filling. I got so full off of the beignets that I could barely put a dent in my hangtown fry. And OMG that crawfish beignet is AMAZINGGGGG. I wished we had more than just the one to share.

    I will definitely be coming back! I want to try the watermelon tea next time and order 10 crawfish beignets!
